<font color="#FF0000">IN HONOR OF A FALLEN COMRADE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 18 19:40:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Regina <br>
In honor of your brother, I am posting a note from a letter I received a couple of months ago from a Marines Family who was also killed in Action.<br><br>
             Our Vietnam Hero<br><br>
I never got to know you, the man we call Greg<br>
Because you were taken from this family by war.<br>
All they have left is a mind full of memories<br>
And all I have is the ability to read your letters<br>
I wonder how things would differ had you lived<br>
But all I have left is your purple heart.<br><br>
They say everything you did came from your heart<br>
And they speak with such pride when they talk about you, Greg,<br>
A happy young life they say you lived,<br>
But you felt it your duty to be a soldier of war.<br>
I can’t get to know you by reading your letters,<br>
I wish you were here with me to help make some memories.<br><br>
They say you were smart and had a great memory<br>
And to a young girl you gave your heart.<br>
The last Joyce heard from you was in a love letter<br>
And never again would she see her fiancée Greg <br>
Because you were taken through the tragedy of war<br>
Aunt Joyce I would have called her had you lived.<br><br>
Everyone mourned because you could have lived,<br>
Together we could have all made great memories,<br>
You were on your way home because you were injured in war<br>
But went back to give them the rest of your heart.<br>
You don’t know how much you are missed Uncle Greg<br>
Because all that remains are your tattered letters.<br><br>
Alone many will grow old re-reading your letters<br>
Thinking about the great life you would have lived,<br>
Upon Grandma’s mantle sits her last picture of Greg,<br>
While scenes from your childhood dance through your memory,<br>
Forever you will live only in their hearts,<br>
You will never come home because of the Vietnam war.<br><br>
Your last breath was taken in the battle field of that war<br>
And never again would they receive one of your letters,<br>
I wish you were here so I could give you my heart,<br>
Your time here on Earth was too short lived,<br>
Never did they expect that you would return as only a memory,<br>
Inscribed on your tombstone is, “We love you Greg.”<br><br>
Written by Greg’s niece, Kimberlee Friesenhahn, <br>
in December 1996<br><br>
Lance Corporal Gregory VanDeWalle, USMC was killed in action on Mother’s day, in 1967. <br>
He lived in San Antonio, Texas. Greg had been assigned to 1st squad, 1st platoon, India company 3rd Battalion 7th Marines, 1st Marine Division. <br><br>
On the evening of May 13, 1967, Greg was assigned to a squad of Marines reinforcing six other Marines assigned to guard the village of Tam Hoa in the Dai Loc District, Quan Nam province South Vietnam. <br><br>
That evening before they moved out, Greg handed over to Marty Martinez, a fellow Marine his belongings, telling him that he would be not be returning to the hill.<br><br>
Early the following morning, A reinforced company of Communist trained North Vietnamese Soldiers overran their fighting position. Greg was killed by a bullet from an AK-47 rifle as he turned to help other Marines trying to repeal the enemy who were by then coming through their perimeters wire<br><br>
The morning, following his death, his Mother awoke from sleep thousands of miles away. She sat up in bed and told her husband, <br><br>
“Greg is dead. I know it, he just spoke to me and said,”<br>
 <br>
“Mom, I’ve been shot!<br>
 I love you, <br>
Tell Joyce, I love her.” <br><br>
Twelve hours later a Marine Corps officer came to Mrs. Van DeWalle front door to advise the family of their son’s death.<br>

